data.name: Label23.Text
data.value: Most cells in your body reproduce through a process called mitosis. These cells are called somatic cells. They contain two complete sets of genetic material, one set from each parent. During mitosis, this genetic material duplicates itself and creates two new genetically identical daughter cells.

data.name: lblTelophase.Text
data.value: Telophase is the final phase of mitosis. During this phase, the nuclear membrane reforms and the cytoplasm splits through a process called cytokinesis. As a result, two identical daughter cells are formed.

data.name: lblMeta.Text
data.value: Metaphase is the second phase of mitosis. During this phase, the chromosomes that were released during prophase, line up along the center of the cell at an imaginary structure called the metaphase plate.

data.name: Label65.Text
data.value:
Although most cells in your body undergo mitosis to reproduce, there are a special kind of cells that do not. These cells are called sex cells and they undergo a process called meiosis to reproduce.
The main difference between mitosis and meiosis is that mitosis creates 2 genetically identical daughter cells while meiosis typically produces 4 gametes which are genetically different.
Meiosis begins with a somatic cell which splits into 2 different daughter cells through meiosis I. These daughter cells have half of the genetic material of a typical somatic cell.
After this, the 2 daughter cells each split again forming 4 genetically different daughter cells, each with half of the genetic material of a somatic cell during meiosis II.
The fact that these cells have half of the genetic material of a typical body cell makes them haploid, whereas the complete set of genetic material is diploid.

data.name: Label67.Text
data.value: Meiosis creates 4 genetically different haploid daughter cells which are our gametes or sex cells. These have half of the typical number of genetic material so that they can combine with another sex cell to form a fertilized egg or zygote and thus create new life.

data.name: Label31.Text
data.value:
The cell theory is the basis for all of biology. It is composed of three statements:
1) All living things are made of cells.
2) All cells come form pre-existing cells.
3) Cells are the basic units of life.

data.name: Label54.Text
data.value:
A strand of DNA is composed of composed of two backbones made of sugar and phosphate. These backbones are connected together by DNA nitrogenous bases.
There are four types of nitrogenous bases and the are always found in pairs of two. The four types are:
Adenine Thymine Cytosine Guanine
They are always paired up with their corresponding nitrogenous base:
Adenine always pairs up with Thymine. Cytosine always pairs up with Guanine.

data.name: Label69.Text
data.value: Most living organisms reproduce through one of two methods, one is through sexual reproduction and the other is through asexual reproduction. Although many just have one method of reproduction, some have both and can reproduce sexually and asexually.

data.name: Label71.Text
data.value:
Asexual reproduction is the production of a new organism without the use of sex cells, or gametes. This means that they typically do not require a partner to reproduce. Organisms can reproduce asexually through binary fission, budding or fragmentation. Their offspring is genetically identical to the parent.
Binary fission is the process in which an organism, typically those that are unicellular, divides into two identical organisms.
Budding is the process in which a small bud, or organism, forms on the parent and then falls off of the parent, creating a genetically identical copy of the parent.
Fragmentation is the process in which a part of an organism falls off and a new organism grows from the part of the parent.

data.name: Label73.Text
data.value:
Sexual reproduction, on the other hand, is the production of an organism with the use of sex cells or through the exchange of genetic material. This typically means that organisms who reproduce sexually require a partner. Organisms can reproduce sexually through internal fertilization, external fertilization, hermaphroditism and conjugation.
Internal fertilization is the process in which two sex cells which are typically dissimilar, come together to form a fertilized egg inside of the organism which grows into a new organism and is then released from the mother when ready.
External fertilization is the process in which multiple eggs are released by female organisms and are fertilized by male sperm outside of the female’s body.
Hermaphroditism is a method of reproduction in which an organism has both male and female sexual reproductive organs and cells. They may be able to reproduce by themselves, or they may require another organism’s sex cells.
Conjugation is the exchange of genetic material between two bacteria.
